Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany
Report on the inspection
preface
Taxes are the main source of income for public budgets.
A focus of the activities of the Court of Auditors should therefore be on the audit of this area.
This applies in particular to VAT fraud.
This alone results in annual tax losses of an estimated EUR 100 billion in the European Union.
At the VI EUROSAI Congress 2005 in Bonn, the participants pointed out the need for increased cooperation.
This allows the auditors, for example, to exchange audit approaches and optimise audit practice.
Value added tax (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.
In 2006, the Court of Auditors of both countries examined for the first time in parallel in the field of VAT.
The relevant audit report was published in 2008.
Since VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the Court of Auditors is needed. This will enable a comprehensive assessment of whether the measures taken are appropriate to effectively address VAT fraud.
The two Court of Auditors decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany Report on the inspection
1. Introduction
Examination number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892
Subject matter: (CZ) Administration of VAT (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter NKÚ), audit
Examination objective:
(CZ) The administration of VAT and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereinafter CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter Germany) should be examined. In addition, the procedures applied by the tax authorities in the field of intergovernmental assistance should be examined.
(D) The audit should evaluate how the financial administration has implemented the recommendations made by the Court of Auditors.
Further audit fields linked to the VAT should also be processed.
The findings made in this respect should be compared to determine whether the taxation procedures can be optimised.
The examination period was the years 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period before the examination period until the completion of the examination.
2. Summary of results and evaluation of parallel testing
The Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed to audit the administration of VAT.
In the previous parallel examination, they had identified suspected cases involving intra-Community transactions:
which made a re-examination appropriate.
On the basis of the audit findings, the two Court of Auditors made recommendations on the management of VAT.
The aim of the audit was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented. In addition, the identified suspected cases should be investigated.
The audit also dealt with other issues. These included selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual administrative assistance in the recovery of VAT claims and the VAT audit of large enterprises.
The Court of Auditors found that:
1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous review
• Recommendation 1: The rules for the registration of taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU
At the initial audit, the Court of Auditors compared the registration procedures for VAT in the two countries and found differences that caused problems.
The Court of Auditors therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxpayers within the EU.
This was also taken up at EU level.
The draft amendment of Council Regulation No 1798/2003 provides for the extension of the current EU databases, including a database containing the identification number of taxpayers.
The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their eventual cancellation.
The Court of Auditors expected Member States to agree on appropriate rules in accordance with their decision of principle to remove unreliable traders from the VAT system as early as possible.
The Member States reached political agreement in ECOFIN on the latest version of the draft.
The above common rules are no longer included. The two Court of Auditors regret that.
They still consider such rules to be important in order to prevent VAT fraud.
• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of summary reports As a result of the first audit, the Court of Auditors recommended Member States that the summary reports (ZM) should be submitted monthly in future.
The amounts of intra-Community transactions could then be reviewed in more detail.
Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of value added tax for the purpose of combating tax fraud in the case of intra-Community transactions has reduced the deadline for supplying the CM to one month.
In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the VAT Act, which came into force on 1 January 2010.
In Germany, the implementation came into force only on 1 July 2010. It has thus not transposed the obligation to submit the monthly fee into national law in due time.
• Recommendation 3: Data comparison of pre-VAT registrations and the ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and a proposal to examine the merger of the procedures for pre-registration of VAT and ZM The German Finance Administration has taken up the recommendation issued by the Federal Audit Court and set up a working group to identify possible to develop solutions.
The work has not yet been completed.
The Federal Court of Auditors will monitor the further development.
• Recommendation 4: Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches to a risk management system at EU level During the initial audit, the two auditors agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by a Member State alone.
Successful criteria and elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.
If this is not done, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.
The Court of Auditors found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems that have both strengths and weaknesses.
The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU - EUROCANET, while the Federal Audit Court focused on German participation in the “Platform for Risk Management “.
2. Verification of selected intra-Community transactions
During the first audit, the Court of Auditors had jointly examined transactions in which it was doubtful whether they had actually been exported or which had been declared differently by the taxpayers of the two States in the pre-VAT declarations (or VAT declarations) or in the VAT declarations.
The Court of Auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between CZ and Germany for inspection.
The audits by the financial offices of both countries were not completed at the completion of the first parallel audit.
The inspection has shown that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed. The respective tax administrations had taken appropriate measures to this end (including subsequent VAT fixing or the prevention of VAT refunds).
3. Examination of selected, particularly risky intra-Community transactions
The audit also included highly risky intra-Community transactions between taxpayers in the EU covered by the EUROCANET system.
EUROCANET is used to identify risky taxpayers.
Member States may participate in this scheme on a voluntary basis.
CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data under EUROCANET.
From the point of view of an active participating State, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
As a result, no information could be obtained on which suppliers with German VAT ID would have been classified as highly risky cases.
The NKU identified both normal business transactions and those suspected of VAT fraud, including carousel fraud.
The FÄs were only able to review high-risk sales to a limited extent. This was particularly true in the case of so-called “missing traders”, whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxpayer.
In case of suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports
, it is recommended that customs and tax authorities cooperate more closely in order to monitor the nature of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the end user.
Germany and a number of other countries have rejected an active participation in EUROCANET, as they do not see a sufficient legal basis.
The Federal Audit Court noted that the German financial administration uses other instruments to identify taxpayers who are liable to risk.
Nevertheless, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.
The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation
was created by EUROFISC.
The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should be incorporated into the planned network for the fight against VAT fraud.
4. Mutual administrative assistance in the recovery of claims
Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.
Therefore, requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in CZ and Germany are handled in the same way.
The Federal Court of Auditors and the NKU compared the statistics that both Member States submitted to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
These statistics contained inconsistencies.
The two Court of Auditors believe that a renewed discussion on statistics at EU level is useful in order to avoid any inconsistencies in the future.
If this is not done, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should contain more information on VAT.
An analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to assist Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.
Both Court of Auditors consider that Member States with a low recovery rate should endeavour to achieve at least the average recovery rate.
The Commission should assist Member States in this process, if so desired.
5. VAT inspection for large enterprises
The Court of Auditors analysed the legal situation with regard to VAT auditing for large enterprises in both countries.
In addition, they used a questionnaire to collect information from the tax authorities which they considered important in this context.
It was clear that the situation in both countries is different.
For the selection of risky cases, the CZ has a system that includes a large amount of relevant data (including information on VAT audits, balance sheet data and profit and loss accounts).
As a result, the VAT control can be effectively controlled and analysed.
A special tax office for large enterprises is to be established in 2012.
There is no comparable system in Germany yet. This complicates the control and analysis of VAT control as a whole.
The German Finance Administration focuses more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from pre-registration or VAT declarations and the ZM.
Various risk management components, which are to be improved, support the evaluation of this data.
