4. Examination of VAT management in selected areas
4.1 Implementation of recommendations from the first joint examination
4.1.1 Implementation of recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of the conditions for registration of taxpayers within the EU
on the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors recommended to adjust the requirements for VAT registration and to introduce new rules for the cancellation of registration in the CZ.
These amended rules should more effectively contain the risk of possible tax evasion.
In certain cases, it was found that the FÄs did not delete the VAT registration of taxpayers if they did not comply with their obligations under the Czech Law No 235/2004 (hereinafter referred to as the “VAT Act”).
Until now, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted any amendment to oblige the FEs to delete them if taxpayers repeatedly do not submit VAT declarations.
In accordance with the Czech VAT Act, the FA may delete the registration of a taxable person ex officio if (a) the taxpayer has not made transactions for 12 consecutive months and has not informed the FA of the reasons for it; (b) the taxable person has not fulfilled his duties under the VAT Act; Taxable persons no longer meet the requirements for tax liability.
The first examination showed that, due to the existing legal situation, FA Prague 1 has to cancel the VAT registration of “foreign taxable persons” 3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year if they were not obliged to register and pay VAT during the current calendar year.
The FA Prague 1 often did not delete the VAT registration of these taxpayers because the relevant provision of the deadline could not be adequately implemented in practice.
The problem was solved by the amendment of the VAT Act, which came into force on 1 January 2009.
Accordingly, the FA is entitled to cancel the registration of a foreign taxpayer if the latter did not provide goods or services entitled to deduction in the previous calendar year, taxable or exempt goods or services.
Recommendation 2
Monthly delivery of the ZM
On the basis of the initial audit, the Court of Auditors recommended to introduce the monthly fee of ZM.
The Council Directive, which shortened the turnaround for issuing the ZM to one month, was implemented in the CZ by the VAT Act, which entered into force on 1 January 2010.
The ZM must now be delivered electronically.
In addition, a ZM must be provided if services whose place of performance is to be determined in accordance with § 9 (1) VAT Act are provided to a person registered as VAT in another Member State.
The prerequisite is that the recipient is obliged to declare and pay the VAT for these services. This obligation is derived from Council Directive 2008/8/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC as regards the place of service.
Recommendation 3
Reconciliation of the data of the pre-VAT registrations and the ZM to increase the reliability of the MIAS data This recommendation related to the German financial administration.
In its ATIS4 system, the Czech Financial Administration automatically checks data on intra-Community turnover from the VAT declarations and the ZM.
Recommendation 4
Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of VAT is an indispensable condition for the smooth functioning of the EU internal market.
That is why the fight against VAT fraud is of primary interest and has received considerable attention in recent years.
Among other things, a study published by the European Commission in October 2009 demonstrates the importance of this.
In this report, an external expert estimated the VAT loss incurred for the 25 Member States in the period 2000 to 2006. After analysing the available data, the tax loss for the period mentioned was estimated at EUR 90 to 113 billion. This was based on the fact that the EU-25 lose an average of 12% of their turnover taxes each year.
The estimated tax loss for CZ in 2006 was 18%.
The first assessment found that a Member State alone cannot develop an effective risk management system (RMS).
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each Member State.
In relation to the RMS, the Czech Court of Auditors examined the system for the exchange of information within the EU (EUROCANET).
Risk intra-Community transactions exported by taxpayers within the EU and recorded in EUROCANET were selected (see Chapter 4.3).
The EUROFISC network aims to optimise administrative assistance in tax matters and to combat VAT fraud more effectively. Cooperation between the competent authorities should be improved in order to identify cases of fraud as early as possible.
Later, EUROFISC could be used as a tool to estimate the risk potential for intra-Community transactions.
The ECOFIN Council approved EUROFISC as early as 7 October 2008 and at the same time adopted the principles governing the functioning of the system.
EUROFISC is a model for EUROCANET, developed by the Belgian financial administration in cooperation with the other Member States and with the support of the European Commission and OLAF7.
The purpose of the system is to detect risky sales and identify entrepreneurs involved in organised VAT fraud.
