4.2 Verification of selected intra-Community transactions
During the first examination, transactions were examined jointly in which there were doubts as to whether they had actually been exported or if there were any inconsistencies in the declarations made by taxable persons in both Member States.
The two Court of Auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries between CZ and Germany for the purpose of inspection, in which the tax examination by the FÄs of the Member State concerned had not yet been completed at the time of the previous joint examination.
1)
In the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxpayer purchased goods worth 22 686 euros from a German taxpayer.
The Czech taxpayer did not declare the acquisition in his VAT declaration, since the German tax period did not have a VAT identification number, but only a tax number for intra-German transactions.
Through international administrative assistance pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the competent Czech FA had received information that, according to German VAT law, the supplier of intra-Community goods does not need a VAT identification number in order to benefit from the exemption of intra-Community supplies of goods.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that, according to the examination of the competent Czech FA, the Czech taxpayer submitted an additional VAT declaration declaring the purchase of goods of the above value and at the same time asserting his right to deduct VAT in the same amount.
2)
A Czech taxpayer is said to have purchased goods worth EUR 12 561 from a German taxable person in the fourth quarter of 2004.
He said, however, that he did not purchase the goods and therefore did not explain it in his VAT declaration.
On the basis of a provision of Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the German Finance Administration refused to process the request because the turnover associated with the acquisition did not exceed the threshold of EUR 15 000.
Since the Czech FA was unable to obtain any documents, the tax inspection remained unsuccessful and the original tax fixing was in place.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that the Czech FA received two spontaneous information from Germany in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, according to which the German taxable person had invoiced the goods in question to a Slovak addressee.
The Czech taxpayer acquired the goods from the Slovak taxpayer and indicated the purchase in his regular VAT declaration for the month of October 2004.
3)
A Czech taxpayer is said to have purchased a car worth 48 500 euros from a German taxpayer in the fourth quarter of 2004.
However, he did not declare an intra-Community acquisition.
In addition, he had not issued a VAT declaration since August 2004. Therefore, the FA set the VAT for the quarter concerned at CZK 0.
On the basis of information provided by Germany in the course of the international exchange of information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the FA requested the taxpayer to submit a subsequent tax return in March 2007, which the taxpayer did not.
The audit established that the FA had carried out further audits in this tax case in 2007. It found that the passenger car concerned had been sold by the taxpayer to a second-hand car dealer in CZ.
The Czech FA carried out an assessment for the December 2004 tax period, setting additional taxes of CZK 295 379 for the purchase and resale of goods from another Member State.
The competent Czech court decided to open insolvency proceedings concerning the property of the Czech taxpayer; an insolvency administrator was appointed.
In the absence of significant assets, the outstanding tax liability is likely to be irrecoverable.
4)
A Czech taxpayer is expected to have delivered new vehicles (passenger cars) totalling EUR 198 167 to Germany in the fourth quarter of 2004 and in the first quarter of 2005.
The reply to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003 stated that a tax criminal proceedings were pending against the German taxpayer in Germany.
The audit carried out by the Federal Audit Court showed that after the completion of the procedure there was evidence of the involvement of the German taxpayer in fraud.
The intra-Community purchase of goods amounting to EUR 182 424 (for 2004) and EUR 369 690 (for 2005) was subject to acquisition taxation.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors revealed that the Czech taxpayer was involved in carousel fraud involving new vehicles.
On the basis of information provided by the German Financial Administration, a VAT audit of the Czech taxpayer took place for the taxation periods April, May and June 2005.
On the basis of the audit findings and the information from the international exchange of information, the FA set an additional VAT of CZK 703 031 for May 2005 and CZK 726 551 for June 2005.
5)
Czech taxpayer A is said to have purchased a machine with a total value of EUR 58 000 from a German taxpayer in February 2005.
In the third quarter of 2004, the German taxpayer is said to have delivered a machine worth EUR 88 027 to Czech taxpayer B. B, however, denied the acquisition.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors revealed that B had acquired the machine from a German company established in CZ.
Czech taxpayer A did not state the purchase of the goods from the said German taxpayer in its VAT declaration.
The German FA's response to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003 showed that the German taxpayer had not made an intra-Community supply of a machine worth EUR 58 000 but a delivery within the CZ.
In the audit audit, the Bundesrechnungshof found that the intra-Community delivery of the machine was classified as domestic delivery after the completion of an audit and that the VAT exemption was subsequently refused.
6)
A German taxpayer is said to have delivered goods worth EUR 11 600 to a Czech taxable person in the third quarter of 2004.
The goods were purchased and later sold in Germany, i.e. in 2005.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that the Czech FA had carried out its assessment on the basis of a supplementary VAT declaration, which inadvertently showed acquisitions from another Member State, including acquisitions in the abovementioned amount.
The Bundesrechnungshof found that, after receiving a response to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the German FA corrected the German taxpayer's VAT declaration and fixed an additional VAT of EUR 1 600.
Due to the resale of the goods in Germany and the corresponding VAT assessment there, an examination is underway.
The ZM of the German taxpayer has not been corrected so far, since in Germany only the taxable person who has surrendered the ZM can correct it.
7)
The competent Czech FA received a request for information from the German Finance Administration in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003 on the issue of acquiring a car worth 47 400 euros in February 2005 by a Czech taxable person.
Following an examination for the 2005 taxation period, the Czech FA fixed the tax liability of the Czech taxpayer at CZK 0 and informed the German FA that it could not confirm the acquisition of the car by the Czech taxpayer.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors revealed that the registration of the Czech VAT payer had been deleted because he had not complied with his tax obligations.
The Czech FA had forwarded the documents to the Czech police.
The German taxpayer has not yet corrected his information in the ZM, but has appealed against the tax decision.
8)
According to MIAS10, between the third quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a German taxable person delivered goods totalling EUR 33 205 to a Czech taxable person, which he did not declare as an intra-Community acquisition.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech FA examined the reasons for the inconsistencies.
The Czech taxpayer made subsequent VAT declarations for the first quarter of 2005.
However, the Czech FA was unable to clarify the difference in the amount of CZK 134 273 during the period from the third quarter of 2004 to the first quarter of 2005. It justified this by the fact that sales for individual quarters could not be accurately allocated and accepted the VAT declarations made.
9)
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxpayer had delivered goods worth 46 854 euros to a Czech taxable person.
For the same period, the Czech taxable person declared the intra-Community purchase of goods worth only EUR 14 856.
As part of the intergovernmental exchange of information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the Czech FA verified the actual value of the supply.
The German response to this request provided three invoices representing a total value of EUR 31 998, i.e. an amount corresponding to the difference between the purchase declared by the Czech taxpayer and the MIAS data.
According to the results of the audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors, following repeated reminders from the FA in January 2007, the Czech taxable person submitted a subsequent VAT declaration for the tax period July 2004.
With this declaration, the taxpayer simultaneously asserted his right to deduct VAT. Its tax liability for the tax period in question therefore remained unchanged.
The audit confirmed that most of the tax procedures relating to the transactions selected for the audit had been completed and that the tax authorities in CZ and Germany had taken appropriate measures (including subsequent VAT fixing or the prevention of VAT refunds).
4.3 Examination of selected cases of risk intra-Community transactions
4.3.1 Findings in the Czech Republic
EUROCANET can be a significant source of information for identifying risky taxpayers in the Member State of acquisition.
In the CZ, the early-warning information obtained from EUROCANET is checked by the competent FA with the purchasers.
Since the first quarter of 2008, CZ has entered the EUROCANET system information on sales and taxable suppliers considered to be at risk.
Nine Czech taxpayers were selected for the audit:
entered into EUROCANET by the financial administrations of other Member States either as suppliers or acquirers.
ThisSegmentIsIntentionAllyLeftBlank
Since the German financial administration did not participate in the exchange of data via EUROCANET, it was not possible to determine whether suppliers with a German VAT identification number were classified as risk-bearing by the German financial administration.
The audit identified both normal transactions and those suspected of carousel fraud or other VAT fraud.
In the cases concerned, the FÄs exchanged information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003:
e.g.:
• The FEs did not identify any suspicion of risk-related transactions during the review of early warning information.
The taxpayers concerned were continuously monitored because their data were stored in EUROCANET.
• In the reviews of risk-related transactions, the FEs failed to demonstrate infringements of the rules for calculating the tax base and VAT on the basis of the submitted accounting documents, even though they found disagreements in the transport and storage of the goods or business relationships with mailbox companies from other Member States.
• The review of individual transactions was complicated because certain taxpayers did not cooperate with the FÄs or could not be contacted.
The competent FÄs reviewed most of the risk-bearing taxpayers and transactions referred to in EUROCANET's early warning reports.
However, their possibilities for verifying risky revenues, especially so-called “missing traders”, are limited.
In particular, a mere examination of the documents can hardly prove fraudulent action by the taxpayer.
Stronger requirements for registration of taxpayers for VAT purposes and greater flexibility in deleting registrations would be helpful in combating VAT fraud.
Taxpayers involved in fraudulent merry-go-round transactions can be registered for VAT purposes in order to simulate fictitious deliveries of goods across the EU or to issue formally correct tax documents to other taxpayers to claim unjustified claims for deduction.
In case of suspicion of carousel fraud related to imports and exports, it is recommended that customs and tax authorities cooperate more closely in order to monitor the nature of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the end user.
Member States may participate in EUROCANET on a voluntary basis.
The fact that three major Member States (Germany, Italy and the United Kingdom) did not participate was seen by the European Parliament at the end of 200811 as a weakness of the system, which should be remedied by setting up a EuroFISC network with mandatory participation.
4.3.2 Findings in Germany
The Federal Court of Auditors evaluated data available at the Federal Central Office for Taxes, including those from EUROCANET.
They served as the basis for the selection of six German taxpayers whose files were reviewed.
Both Germany and a number of other countries refused active participation in EUROCANET.
Therefore, Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not itself send data to Brussels, but is only a recipient of EuroCanet data.
This is justified by the fact that “from the point of view of the Federal Government
no unambiguous legal basis [exists] which would allow the tax secrecy existing in Germany to be broken.
In addition, the Federal Government does not have reliable information on how information sent by the Member States is processed within the framework of EUROCANET.” 12 Since October 2007, the Federal Central Office for Taxes has evaluated the EUROCANET data and transmits them to the federal and state tax authorities on the basis of a coordinated procedure.
The German FÄs receive control notices concerning the direct business relationships of taxpayers registered with them with companies from other EU countries, recorded in EUROCANET.
However, the respective German FA does not receive information as to whether the company from the aforementioned other EU Member State has business relations with a company resident in another Member State which is also in business relationship with the German company in the control communication.
4.3.3 Evaluation
CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET, while Germany has only a passive status.
From the point of view of an active participant, it is unsatisfactory for other Member States to refuse active participation.
Accordingly, the test had to be carried out differently in this area.
However, significant differences in the success of the detection of VAT fraud could not be identified. This is due to the fact that EUROCANET is only one component of the risk management system.
However, the financial administrations of both countries have a variety of other instruments to detect fraudulent transactions. Nevertheless, it is necessary to develop a comprehensive risk management system within the EU.
The Council of the European Union agreed on a draft Regulaties13 establishing EUROFISC, a network for combating VAT fraud.
Member States should share the experience gained so far with EUROCANET at European level and contribute to this network.
