4.4 Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
4.4.1 Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic
The legislation on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims in the EU is essentially based on
Council Directive 76/308/EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to measures forming part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, as well as levies and duties;
Council Directive 2001/44/EC amending Council Directive 76/308/EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to actions forming part of the system of financing of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, and of levies and duties; and as regards VAT and certain excise duties; and
Commission Directive 2002/94/EC laying down detailed rules for the application of certain articles of Directive 76/308/EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to certain duties, duties, taxes and other measures.
The CZ implemented Council Directive 76/308/EEC by Law No 252/2000 on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims.
Following the adoption of Council Directive 2001/44/EC, it also had to be transposed into Czech law. At the same time, an amendment to the aforementioned law was required.
In this context, Amendment No 191/2004 on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims was adopted.
A new relevant legislation was adopted by Commission Regulation (EC) No 1179/2008 of 28 November 2008.
The annexes to this Regulation contain new application forms to be used from 1 January 2009. Furthermore, the Regulation makes electronic transmission compulsory and obliges the requesting authority to certify the conformity of all documents sent with the original.
The main principles of international administrative assistance for the recovery of claims are:
1. the principle of reciprocity shall apply;
2. Assistance shall always be provided only upon request and upon fulfilment of all conditions;
3. Administrative assistance shall not cover claims which are regarded as a criminal sanction in the requested State;
4. The intergovernmental assistance procedure for the recovery of claims shall be carried out in accordance with the national law of the requested State;
5. In the recovery procedure, foreign claims shall not take precedence over domestic claims;
6. Assistance shall be provided only for the recovery of undisputed claims;
7. The principle of exhaustion applies: the requesting State shall use all means to recover the claim under national law.
Law No 191/2004 provides for three forms of mutual assistance: information, service of acts and recovery.
Procedures for outgoing requests to other EU Member States
The competent FA shall transmit the request for information, the request for notification of legal acts or the request for recovery together with the documents concerned electronically to the Ministry of Finance of the CZ via the relevant Finance Directorate.
The Ministry of Finance of the CZ shall arrange for the translation of the request into the language concerned, scan it with all attachments and send it to the competent tax authority of the State concerned via the communication network or the common interface CCN/CSI.
A request for recovery aid must fulfil the following condition: the claim must exceed EUR 1 500 and must not be older than five years.
The requested authority may refuse recovery if the requirements are not met.
Procedures for incoming requests from other Member States
The CZ Ministry of Finance shall confirm receipt of requests from other Member States as soon as possible, at the latest within seven days.
If it decides not to accept the request, it shall inform the applicant authority of the reasons for the refusal, specifying the specific provisions of the Directive on which it is based.
The notification shall be sent no later than three months after the date of receipt of the confirmation of receipt of the request.
Upon receipt of the request, the Ministry of Finance shall verify that the request meets all legal requirements.
It shall then forward the request to the competent FA through the relevant Financial Directorate. If the request for recovery is accepted, the FA shall, inter alia, determine the financial situation of the debtor, e.g. by extracts from the land register, inquiries about existing bank accounts and registration of a vehicle with the registration office.
