4.4.4 Comparison and evaluation
In the case of recovery, the provisions of EU law apply to intergovernmental assistance for all EU Member States.
The procedures for processing requests are therefore similar in CZ and Germany.
The Federal Court of Auditors and the NKÚ have compared the statistics submitted by the two Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
There were disagreements.
In its 200620 report, the European Commission recommended Member States to compile their statistics with greater care.
In 200921, the Commission concluded that despite a larger number of requests for assistance, the discrepancies in statistics have decreased.
Both Court of Auditors consider a renewed discussion at EU level on statistics to be useful in order to avoid the remaining discrepancies in the future.
If this is not done, the statistics are conditionally meaningful and cannot be used for comparisons.
In addition, the Court of Auditors considers that the statistics should show both the annual number of requests and the type of receivables (e.g. VAT, income tax) and the amount of sums recovered per Member State.
Through a more detailed analysis of the statistics submitted by the Member States, the Commission could assist Member States in assessing their measures to combat VAT fraud.
Since the recovery rate can be calculated per Member State, the Court of Auditors argue that the low rate Member States should aim at at least the average recovery rate within the EU.
At the request of a Member State, the Commission could play an active role in this.
The foreign recovery requests received by the Ministry of Finance CZ were forwarded to the competent FÄs, particularly in 2006 and 2007.
